  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 팔분(八分) : '
    value: 글씨체의 일종.
english:
  title: Sharing Rhymes with Sook Do, Drawing the Theme of Half Clouds and Rain Over the Chu River and Wu Gorge, Sent to Jung In
  author: Nam Hyo-on
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Why should fortune and decline weigh upon the heart?
    A hundred years—no more than a single dream of millet.
    In the quiet gate, a hungry kite cries out.
    I am content with this humble snail shell of a dwelling.

    The pomegranate's crimson petals fall,
    while the gardens begin their gradual fever of heat.
    A single thread of cool rain on the lotus pond—
    black clouds bury the flatlands below.

    Alone I lean upon my desk,
    with whom shall I share this solitary joy?
    Now and then I compose five-character verses,
    seeking response from a kindred spirit's brush.

    You, since youth, have known disappointment,
    ten years spent exhausting the ancient texts.
    Yet like Sima Qian you love to wander,
    your footprints reaching every corner of these eastern lands.
    Your eyes have crossed the southern seas,
    your poems pierce through the clouds of five sacred peaks.
    Your prose grows greater day by day,
    paper and brush wearing thin with your diligence.

    Fifteen years we have walked this friendship together,
    and many times I have heard your words of warning.
    On rainy nights when the blue lamp burns bright,
    I write these verses in seal script to send to you.

    How few in this world are truly worthy?
    I count myself blessed to number you among my one or two friends.
    Yet I lament how the affairs of the world betray our intentions—
    we cannot see them plainly even once.

    The poet of immortals, Master An Zyting,
    has already become master of the gulls and herons.
    That pure and austere scholar, detached from worldly things,
    I hear has taken refuge in Buddhist practice.

    Only you, Sook Do, speak of poetry still.
    With bamboo eaves where wind and rain conspire,
    when a poem is completed, I shall call you here—
    I wait, incense burning on the Boshan altar.
  footnotes:
    - Sima Qian (司馬遷), the legendary historian and author of the Records of the Grand Historian, is invoked here as a symbol of one who traveled extensively despite hardship to gather knowledge.
    - The five sacred peaks (五鎭) refer to Taoism's five holy mountains.
    - Seal script (八分, pa-bun) refers to an ancient style of Chinese calligraphy, used here to suggest a formal, deliberate act of literary composition.
    - The Boshan altar (博山香) is a reference to a decorative incense burner, suggesting refined aesthetic devotion.
